<html><body><div style=3D"color:#000; background-color:#fff; font-family:ti=
mes new roman, new york, times, serif;font-size:10pt"><div id=3D"content">=
=0A=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09<article id=3D"maincontent">=0A=09=09=09=09<h1>B=
randenburg v. Ohio - 395 U.S. 444 (1969)</h1><br>=0A=0A<ul class=3D"supreme=
links"><li>=0A=09=09=09<a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/u=
s/395/444/">Syllabus</a>=0A=09=09=09</li><li>=0A=09=09=09Case=09=09=09</li>=
</ul>=0A<span class=3D"headertext"><h2>U.S. Supreme Court</h2><h3>Brandenbu=
rg v. Ohio, 395 U.S.  444 (1969)</h3><div><b>Brandenburg v. Ohio</b></div><=
div><b>No. 492</b></div><div><b>Argued February 27, 1969</b></div><div><b>D=
ecided June 9, 1969</b></div><div><b>395 U.S. 444</b></div><div><em>APPEAL =
FROM THE SUPREME COURT OF OHIO=0A</em></div>=0A<div><em><em>Syllabus</em>=
=0A</em></div>=0A<div>Appellant, a Ku Klux Klan leader, was convicted under=
 the Ohio Criminal Syndicalism statute for</div>=0A<div>"advocat[ing] . . .=
 the duty, necessity, or propriety of crime, =0Asabotage, violence, or unla=
wful methods of terrorism as a means of =0Aaccomplishing industrial or poli=
tical reform"</div>=0A<div>and for</div>=0A<div>"voluntarily assembl[ing] w=
ith any society, group or assemblage of =0Apersons formed to teach or advoc=
ate the doctrines of criminal =0Asyndicalism."</div>=0A<div>Neither the ind=
ictment nor the trial judge's instructions refined the=0A statute's definit=
ion of the crime in terms of mere advocacy not =0Adistinguished from incite=
ment to imminent lawless action.</div>=0A<div><em>Held:</em>  Since the sta=
tute, by its words and as applied, =0Apurports to punish mere advocacy and =
to forbid, on pain of criminal =0Apunishment, assembly with others merely t=
o advocate the described type =0Aof action, it falls within the condemnatio=
n of the First and Fourteenth =0AAmendments.  Freedoms of speech and press =
do not permit a State to =0Aforbid advocacy of the use of force or of law v=
iolation except where =0Asuch advocacy is directed to inciting or producing=
 imminent lawless =0Aaction and is likely to incite or produce such action.=
  <em>Whitney v. California,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"htt=
p://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/274/357/case.html">274 U. S. 357</a=
></span>, overruled.</div>=0A<div><em>Reversed.</em></div>=0A<div>PER CURIA=
M.</div>=0A<div>The appellant, a leader of a Ku Klux Klan group, was convic=
ted under =0Athe Ohio Criminal Syndicalism statute for "advocat[ing] . . . =
the duty, =0Anecessity, or propriety </div><div><a href=3D"" class=3D"page-=
number" name=3D"445">Page 395 U. S. 445</a></div><div>=0A of crime, sabotag=
e, violence, or unlawful methods of terrorism as a =0Ameans of accomplishin=
g industrial or political reform" and for</div>=0A<div>"voluntarily assembl=
[ing] with any society, group, or assemblage of =0Apersons formed to teach =
or advocate the doctrines of criminal =0Asyndicalism."</div>=0A<div>Ohio Re=
v.Code Ann. =A7 2923.13.  He was fined $1,000 and sentenced to =0Aone to 10=
 years' imprisonment.  The appellant challenged the =0Aconstitutionality of=
 the criminal syndicalism statute under the First =0Aand Fourteenth Amendme=
nts to the United States Constitution, but the =0Aintermediate appellate co=
urt of Ohio affirmed his conviction without =0Aopinion.  The Supreme Court =
of Ohio dismissed his appeal <em>sua sponte</em>=0A "for the reason that no=
 substantial constitutional question exists =0Aherein."  It did not file an=
 opinion or explain its conclusions.  Appeal=0A was taken to this Court, an=
d we noted probable jurisdiction.  <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"ht=
tp://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/393/87/case.html#94">393 U. S. 94<=
/a></span> (196).  We reverse.</div>=0A<div>The record shows that a man, id=
entified at trial as the appellant, =0Atelephoned an announcer-reporter on =
the staff of a Cincinnati television=0A station and invited him to come to =
a Ku Klux Klan "rally" to be held at=0A a farm in Hamilton County.  With th=
e cooperation of the organizers, the=0A reporter and a cameraman attended t=
he meeting and filmed the events.  =0APortions of the films were later broa=
dcast on the local station and on a=0A national network.</div>=0A<div>The p=
rosecution's case rested on the films and on testimony =0Aidentifying the a=
ppellant as the person who communicated with the =0Areporter and who spoke =
at the rally.  The State also introduced into =0Aevidence several articles =
appearing in the film, including a pistol, a =0Arifle, a shotgun, ammunitio=
n, a Bible, and a red hood worn by the =0Aspeaker in the films.</div>=0A<di=
v>One film showed 12 hooded figures, some of whom carried firearms.  =0AThe=
y were gathered around a large wooden cross, which they burned.  No =0Aone =
was present </div><div><a href=3D"" class=3D"page-number" name=3D"446">Page=
 395 U. S. 446</a></div><div>=0A other than the participants and the newsme=
n who made the film.  Most of=0A the words uttered during the scene were in=
comprehensible when the film =0Awas projected, but scattered phrases could =
be understood that were =0Aderogatory of Negroes and, in one instance, of J=
ews. [<a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/395/444/case.ht=
ml#F1" name=3D"T1">Footnote 1</a>]  Another scene on the same film showed t=
he appellant, in Klan regalia, making a speech.  The speech, in full, was a=
s follows:</div>=0A<div>"This is an organizers' meeting.  We have had quite=
 a few members =0Ahere today which are -- we have hundreds, hundreds of mem=
bers throughout=0A the State of Ohio.  I can quote from a newspaper clippin=
g from the =0AColumbus, Ohio, Dispatch, five weeks ago Sunday morning.  The=
 Klan has =0Amore members in the State of Ohio than does any other organiza=
tion.  =0AWe're not a revengent organization, but if our President, our Con=
gress, =0Aour Supreme Court, continues to suppress the white, Caucasian rac=
e, it's=0A possible that there might have to be some revengeance taken."</d=
iv>=0A<div>"We are marching on Congress July the Fourth, four hundred thous=
and =0Astrong.  From there, we are dividing into two groups, one group to m=
arch=0A on St. Augustine, Florida, the other group to march into Mississipp=
i.  =0AThank you.  "</div><div><a href=3D"" class=3D"page-number" name=3D"4=
47">Page 395 U. S. 447</a></div>=0A<div>The second film showed six hooded f=
igures one of whom, later =0Aidentified as the appellant, repeated a speech=
 very similar to that =0Arecorded on the first film.  The reference to the =
possibility of =0A"revengeance" was omitted, and one sentence was added:  "=
Personally, I =0Abelieve the nigger should be returned to Africa, the Jew r=
eturned to =0AIsrael."  Though some of the figures in the films carried wea=
pons, the =0Aspeaker did not.</div>=0A<div>The Ohio Criminal Syndicalism St=
atute was enacted in 1919.  From 1917=0A to 1920, identical or quite simila=
r laws were adopted by 20 States and =0Atwo territories.  E. Dowell, A Hist=
ory of Criminal Syndicalism =0ALegislation in the United States 21 (1939). =
 In 1927, this Court =0Asustained the constitutionality of California's Cri=
minal Syndicalism =0AAct, Cal.Penal Code =A7=A7 11400-11402, the text of wh=
ich is quite similar =0Ato that of the laws of Ohio.  <em>Whitney v. Califo=
rnia,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/=
cases/federal/us/274/357/case.html">274 U. S. 357</a></span>=0A (1927).  Th=
e Court upheld the statute on the ground that, without more,=0A "advocating=
" violent means to effect political and economic change =0Ainvolves such da=
nger to the security of the State that the State may =0Aoutlaw it.  <em>Cf.=
 Fiske v. Kansas,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme=
.justia.com/cases/federal/us/274/380/case.html">274 U. S. 380</a></span> (1=
927).  But <em>Whitney</em> has been thoroughly discredited by later decisi=
ons.  <em>See Dennis v. United States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a h=
ref=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/341/494/case.html">341 U.=
 S. 494</a></span>, at  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http:=
//supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/341/494/case.html#507">341 U. S. 507<=
/a></span>=0A (1951).  These later decisions have fashioned the principle t=
hat the =0Aconstitutional guarantees of free speech and free press do not p=
ermit a =0AState to forbid or proscribe advocacy of the use of force or of =
law =0Aviolation except where such advocacy is directed to inciting or =0Ap=
roducing imminent lawless action and is likely to incite or produce =0Asuch=
 action. [<a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/395/444/cas=
e.html#F2" name=3D"T2">Footnote 2</a>]  As we </div><div><a href=3D"" class=
=3D"page-number" name=3D"448">Page 395 U. S. 448</a></div><div> said in <em=
>Noto v. United States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://s=
upreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/367/290/case.html">367 U. S. 290</a></sp=
an>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.c=
om/cases/federal/us/367/290/case.html#297">367 U. S. 297</a></span>-298 (19=
61),</div>=0A<div>"the mere abstract teaching . . . of the moral propriety =
or even =0Amoral necessity for a resort to force and violence is not the sa=
me as =0Apreparing a group for violent action and steeling it to such actio=
n."</div>=0A<div><em>See also Herndon v. Lowry,</em> <span class=3D"l-lefto=
ver"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/301/242/case.htm=
l">301 U. S. 242</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D=
"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/301/242/case.html#259">301 U. S=
. 259</a></span>-261 (1937); <em>Bond v. Floyd,</em> <span class=3D"l-lefto=
ver"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/385/116/case.htm=
l">385 U. S. 116</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D=
"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/385/116/case.html#134">385 U. S=
. 134</a></span>=0A (1966).  A statute which fails to draw this distinction=
 impermissibly =0Aintrudes upon the freedoms guaranteed by the First and Fo=
urteenth =0AAmendments.  It sweeps within its condemnation speech which our=
 =0AConstitution has immunized from governmental control.  <em>Cf. Yates v.=
 United States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.j=
ustia.com/cases/federal/us/354/298/case.html">354 U. S. 298</a></span> (195=
7); <em>De Jonge v. Oregon,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http=
://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/299/353/case.html">299 U. S. 353</a>=
</span> (1937); <em>Stromberg v. California,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover=
"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/283/359/case.html">=
283 U. S. 359</a></span> (1931).  <em>See also United States v. Robel,</em>=
 <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/fede=
ral/us/389/258/case.html">389 U. S. 258</a></span> (1967); <em>Keyishian v.=
 Board of Regents,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://suprem=
e.justia.com/cases/federal/us/385/589/case.html">385 U. S. 589</a></span> (=
1967); <em>Elfbrandt v. Russell,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a
 href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/384/11/case.html">384 U=
. S. 11</a></span> (1966); <em>Aptheker v. Secretary of State,</em> <span c=
lass=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/3=
78/500/case.html">378 U. S. 500</a></span> (1964); <em>Baggett v. Bullitt,<=
/em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/=
federal/us/377/360/case.html">377 U. S. 360</a></span> (1964).</div>=0A<div=
>Measured by this test, Ohio's Criminal Syndicalism Act cannot be =0Asustai=
ned.  The Act punishes persons who "advocate or teach the duty, =0Anecessit=
y, or propriety" of violence "as a means of accomplishing =0Aindustrial or =
political reform"; or who publish or circulate or display =0Aany book or pa=
per containing such advocacy; or who "justify" the =0Acommission of violent=
 acts "with intent to exemplify, spread or advocate=0A the propriety of the=
 doctrines of criminal syndicalism"; or who =0A"voluntarily assemble" with =
a group formed "to teach or advocate the =0Adoctrines of criminal syndicali=
sm."  Neither the indictment nor the =0Atrial judge's instructions to the j=
ury in any way refined the statute's =0Abald definition of the crime </div>=
<div><a href=3D"" class=3D"page-number" name=3D"449">Page 395 U. S. 449</a>=
</div><div> in terms of mere advocacy not distinguished from incitement to =
imminent lawless action. [<a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federa=
l/us/395/444/case.html#F3" name=3D"T3">Footnote 3</a>]</div>=0A<div>Accordi=
ngly, we are here confronted with a statute which, by its own =0Awords and =
as applied, purports to punish mere advocacy and to forbid, on=0A pain of c=
riminal punishment, assembly with others merely to advocate =0Athe describe=
d type of action. [<a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/39=
5/444/case.html#F4" name=3D"T4">Footnote 4</a>]  Such a statute falls withi=
n the condemnation of the First and Fourteenth Amendments.  The contrary te=
aching of <em>Whitney v. California, supra,</em> cannot be supported, and t=
hat decision is therefore overruled.</div>=0A<div><em>Reversed.</em></div>=
=0A<div>[<a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/395/444/case=
.html#T1" name=3D"F1">Footnote 1</a>]</div>=0A<div>The significant portions=
 that could be understood were:</div>=0A<div>"How far is the nigger going t=
o -- yeah."</div>=0A<div>"This is what we are going to do to the niggers."<=
/div>=0A<div>"A dirty nigger."</div>=0A<div>"Send the Jews back to Israel."=
</div>=0A<div>"Let's give them back to the dark garden."</div>=0A<div>"Save=
 America."</div>=0A<div>"Let's go back to constitutional betterment."</div>=
=0A<div>"Bury the niggers."</div>=0A<div>"We intend to do our part."</div>=
=0A<div>"Give us our state rights."</div>=0A<div>"Freedom for the whites."<=
/div>=0A<div>"Nigger will have to fight for every inch he gets from now on.=
"</div>=0A<div>[<a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/395/4=
44/case.html#T2" name=3D"F2">Footnote 2</a>]</div>=0A<div>It was on the the=
ory that the Smith Act, 54 Stat. 670, 18 U.S.C. =A7 =0A35, embodied such a =
principle and that it had been applied only in =0Aconformity with it that t=
his Court sustained the Act's =0Aconstitutionality.  <em>Dennis v. United S=
tates,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com=
/cases/federal/us/341/494/case.html">341 U. S. 494</a></span> (1951).  That=
 this was the basis for <em>Dennis</em> was emphasized in <em>Yates v. Unit=
ed States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia=
.com/cases/federal/us/354/298/case.html">354 U. S. 298</a></span>,  <span c=
lass=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/fede=
ral/us/354/298/case.html#320">354 U. S. 320</a></span>-324=0A (1957), in wh=
ich the Court overturned convictions for advocacy of the =0Aforcible overth=
row of the Government under the Smith Act, because the =0Atrial judge's ins=
tructions had allowed conviction for mere advocacy, =0Aunrelated to its ten=
dency to produce forcible action.</div>=0A<div>[<a href=3D"http://supreme.j=
ustia.com/cases/federal/us/395/444/case.html#T3" name=3D"F3">Footnote 3</a>=
]</div>=0A<div>The first count of the indictment charged that appellant</di=
v>=0A<div>"did unlawfully by word of mouth advocate the necessity, or propr=
iety=0A of crime, violence, or unlawful methods of terrorism as a means of =
=0Aaccomplishing political reform. . . ."</div>=0A<div>The second count cha=
rged that appellant "did unlawfully voluntarily =0Aassemble with a group or=
 assemblage of persons formed to advocate the =0Adoctrines of criminal synd=
icalism. . . ."  The trial judge's charge =0Amerely followed the language o=
f the indictment.  No construction of the =0Astatute by the Ohio courts has=
 brought it within constitutionally =0Apermissible limits.  The Ohio Suprem=
e Court has considered the statute =0Ain only one previous case, <em>State =
v. Kassay,</em> 126 Ohio St. 177, 184 N.E. 521 (1932), where the constituti=
onality of the statute was sustained.</div>=0A<div>[<a href=3D"http://supre=
me.justia.com/cases/federal/us/395/444/case.html#T4" name=3D"F4">Footnote 4=
</a>]</div>=0A<div>Statutes affecting the right of assembly, like those tou=
ching on =0Afreedom of speech, must observe the established distinctions be=
tween =0Amere advocacy and incitement to imminent lawless action, for, as C=
hief =0AJustice Hughes wrote in <em>De Jonge v. Oregon, supra,</em> at  <sp=
an class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/=
federal/us/299/353/case.html#364">299 U. S. 364</a></span>:  "The right of =
peaceable assembly is a right cognate to those of free speech and free pres=
s, and is equally fundamental."  <em>See also United States v. Cruikshank,<=
/em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/=
federal/us/92/542/case.html">92 U. S. 542</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-nor=
maldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/92/542=
/case.html#552">92 U. S. 552</a></span> (1876); <em>Hague v. CIO,</em> <spa=
n class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/u=
s/307/496/case.html">307 U. S. 496</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigi=
tafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/307/496/case.=
html#513">307 U. S. 513</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a
 href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/307/496/case.html#519">=
307 U. S. 519</a></span> (1939); <em>NAACP v. Alabama ex rel. Patterson,</e=
m> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/fe=
deral/us/357/449/case.html">357 U. S. 449</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-nor=
maldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/357/44=
9/case.html#460">357 U. S. 460</a></span>-461 (1958).</div>=0A<div>MR. JUST=
ICE BLACK, concurring.</div>=0A<div>I agree with the views expressed by MR.=
 JUSTICE DOUGLAS in his =0Aconcurring opinion in this case that the "clear =
and present danger" =0Adoctrine should have no place </div><div><a href=3D"=
" class=3D"page-number" name=3D"450">Page 395 U. S. 450</a></div><div> in t=
he interpretation of the First Amendment.  I join the Court's opinion, whic=
h, as I understand it, simply cites <em>Dennis v. United States,</em> <span=
 class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us=
/341/494/case.html">341 U. S. 494</a></span> (1951), but does not indicate =
any agreement on the Court's part with the "clear and present danger" doctr=
ine on which <em>Dennis</em> purported to rely.</div>=0A<div>MR. JUSTICE DO=
UGLAS, concurring.</div>=0A<div>While I join the opinion of the Court, I de=
sire to enter a <em>caveat.</em></div>=0A<div>The "clear and present danger=
" test was adumbrated by Mr. Justice =0AHolmes in a case arising during Wor=
ld War I -- a war "declared" by the =0ACongress, not by the Chief Executive=
.  The case was <em>Schenck v. United States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftove=
r"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/249/47/case.html">=
249 U. S. 47</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"htt=
p://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/249/47/case.html#52">249 U. S. 52</=
a></span>,=0A where the defendant was charged with attempts to cause insubo=
rdination =0Ain the military and obstruction of enlistment.  The pamphlets =
that were =0Adistributed urged resistance to the draft, denounced conscript=
ion, and =0Aimpugned the motives of those backing the war effort.  The Firs=
t =0AAmendment was tendered as a defense.  Mr. Justice Holmes, in rejecting=
 =0Athat defense, said:</div>=0A<div>"The question in every case is whether=
 the words used are used in =0Asuch circumstances and are of such a nature =
as to create a clear and =0Apresent danger that they will bring about the s=
ubstantive evils that =0ACongress has a right to prevent.  It is a question=
 of proximity and =0Adegree."</div>=0A<div><em>Frohwerk v. United States,</=
em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/f=
ederal/us/249/204/case.html">249 U. S. 204</a></span>,=0A also authored by =
Mr. Justice Holmes, involved prosecution and =0Apunishment for publication =
of articles very critical of the war effort =0Ain World War I.  <em>Schenck=
</em> was referred to as a conviction for obstructing security "by words of=
 persuasion."  <em>Id.</em> at  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=
=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/249/204/case.html#206">249 U=
. S. 206</a></span>.  And the conviction in <em>Frohwerk</em> was sustained=
 because "the circulation of the paper was </div><div><a href=3D"" class=3D=
"page-number" name=3D"451">Page 395 U. S. 451</a></div><div> in quarters wh=
ere a little breath would be enough to kindle a flame."  <em>Id.</em> at  <=
span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/case=
s/federal/us/249/204/case.html#209">249 U. S. 209</a></span>.</div>=0A<div>=
<em>Debs v. United States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http:=
//supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/249/211/case.html">249 U. S. 211</a><=
/span>,=0A was the third of the trilogy of the 1918 Term.  Debs was convict=
ed of =0Aspeaking in opposition to the war where his "opposition was so exp=
ressed=0A that its natural and intended effect would be to obstruct recruit=
ing." =0A <em>Id.</em> at  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"ht=
tp://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/249/211/case.html#215">249 U. S. 2=
15</a></span>.</div>=0A<div>"If that was intended, and if, in all the circu=
mstances, that would =0Abe its probable effect, it would not be protected b=
y reason of its being=0A part of a general program and expressions of a gen=
eral and =0Aconscientious belief."</div>=0A<div><em>Ibid.</em></div>=0A<div=
>In the 1919 Term, the Court applied the <em>Schenck</em> doctrine to affir=
m the convictions of other dissidents in World War I.  <em>Abrams v. United=
 States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.c=
om/cases/federal/us/250/616/case.html">250 U. S. 616</a></span>, was one in=
stance.  Mr. Justice Holmes, with whom Mr. Justice Brandeis concurred, diss=
ented.  While adhering to <em>Schenck,</em> he did not think that, on the f=
acts, a case for overriding the First Amendment had been made out:</div>=0A=
<div>"It is only the present danger of immediate evil or an intent to =0Abr=
ing it about that warrants Congress in setting a limit to the =0Aexpression=
 of opinion where private rights are not concerned.  Congress =0Acertainly =
cannot forbid all effort to change the mind of the country."</div>=0A<div><=
em>Id.</em> at  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://suprem=
e.justia.com/cases/federal/us/250/616/case.html#628">250 U. S. 628</a></spa=
n>.</div>=0A<div>Another instance was <em>Schaefer v. United States,</em> <=
span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federa=
l/us/251/466/case.html">251 U. S. 466</a></span>, in which Mr. Justice Bran=
deis, joined by Mr. Justice Holmes, dissented.  A third was <em>Pierce v. U=
nited States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.jus=
tia.com/cases/federal/us/252/239/case.html">252 U. S. 239</a></span>, in wh=
ich, again, Mr. Justice Brandeis, joined by Mr. Justice Holmes, dissented.<=
/div>=0A<div>Those, then, were the World War I cases that put the gloss of =
"clear =0Aand present danger" on the First Amendment.  Whether the war powe=
r -- =0Athe greatest leveler of them all -- is adequate to sustain that doc=
trine=0A is debatable.  </div><div><a href=3D"" class=3D"page-number" name=
=3D"452">Page 395 U. S. 452</a></div><div> The dissents in <em>Abrams, Scha=
efer,</em> and <em>Pierce</em>=0A show how easily "clear and present danger=
" is manipulated to crush what=0A Brandeis called "[t]he fundamental right =
of free men to strive for =0Abetter conditions through new legislation and =
new institutions" by =0Aargument and discourse (<em>Pierce v. United States=
, supra,</em> at  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supr=
eme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/252/273/case.html">252 U. S. 273</a></span>=
)=0A even in time of war.  Though I doubt if the "clear and present danger"=
 =0Atest is congenial to the First Amendment in time of a declared war, I a=
m=0A certain it is not reconcilable with the First Amendment in days of =0A=
peace.</div>=0A<div>The Court quite properly overrules <em>Whitney v. Calif=
ornia,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com=
/cases/federal/us/274/357/case.html">274 U. S. 357</a></span>, which involv=
ed advocacy of ideas which the majority of the Court deemed unsound and dan=
gerous.</div>=0A<div>Mr. Justice Holmes, though never formally abandoning t=
he "clear and =0Apresent danger" test, moved closer to the First Amendment =
ideal when he =0Asaid in dissent in <em>Gitlow v. New York,</em> <span clas=
s=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/268/=
652/case.html">268 U. S. 652</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter=
"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/268/652/case.html#6=
73">268 U. S. 673</a></span>:</div>=0A<div>"Every idea is an incitement.  I=
t offers itself for belief, and, if =0Abelieved, it is acted on unless some=
 other belief outweighs it or some =0Afailure of energy stifles the movemen=
t at its birth.  The only =0Adifference between the expression of an opinio=
n and an incitement in the=0A narrower sense is the speaker's enthusiasm fo=
r the result.  Eloquence =0Amay set fire to reason.  But whatever may be th=
ought of the redundant =0Adiscourse before us, it had no chance of starting=
 a present =0Aconflagration.  If, in the long run, the beliefs expressed in=
 =0Aproletarian dictatorship are destined to be accepted by the dominant =
=0Aforces of the community, the only meaning of free speech is that they =
=0Ashould be given their chance and have their way."</div>=0A<div>We have n=
ever been faithful to the philosophy of that dissent. </div><div><a href=3D=
"" class=3D"page-number" name=3D"453">Page 395 U. S. 453</a></div>=0A<div>T=
he Court, in <em>Herndon v. Lowry,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=
=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/301/242/case.html">301 U. S.=
 242</a></span>,=0A overturned a conviction for exercising First Amendment =
rights to incite=0A insurrection because of lack of evidence of incitement.=
  <em>Id.</em> at  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://sup=
reme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/301/242/case.html#259">301 U. S. 259</a></=
span>-261.  <em>And see Hartzel v. United States,</em> <span class=3D"l-lef=
tover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/322/680/case.h=
tml">322 U. S. 680</a></span>.  In <em>Bridges v. California,</em> <span cl=
ass=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/31=
4/252/case.html">314 U. S. 252</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitaft=
er"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/314/252/case.html=
#261">314 U. S. 261</a></span>-263,=0A we approved the "clear and present d=
anger" test in an elaborate dictum =0Athat tightened it and confined it to =
a narrow category.  But in <em>Dennis v. United States,</em> <span class=3D=
"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/341/494/=
case.html">341 U. S. 494</a></span>, we opened wide the door, distorting th=
e "clear and present danger" test beyond recognition. [<a href=3D"http://su=
preme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/395/444/case.html#F2/1" name=3D"T2/1">Foo=
tnote 2/1</a>]</div>=0A<div>In that case, the prosecution dubbed an agreeme=
nt to teach the =0AMarxist creed a "conspiracy."  The case was submitted to=
 a jury on a =0Acharge that the jury could not convict unless it found that=
 the =0Adefendants "intended to overthrow the Government as speedily as =0A=
circumstances would permit.'"  <em>Id.</em> at  <span class=3D"l-normaldigi=
tafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/341/494/case.=
html#509">341 U. S. 509</a></span>-511.  The Court sustained convictions un=
der that charge, construing it to mean a determination of</div>=0A<div>""wh=
ether the gravity of the <em>evil,' discounted by its improbability, justif=
ies such invasion of free speech as is necessary to avoid the danger." [<a =
href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/395/444/case.html#F2/2" =
name=3D"T2/2">Footnote 2/2</a>]" </em></div>=0A<div><em>Id.</em> at  <span =
class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/fed=
eral/us/341/494/case.html#510">341 U. S. 510</a></span>, quoting from <em>U=
nited States v. Dennis,</em> 183 F.2d 201, 212.</div>=0A<div>Out of the "cl=
ear and present danger" test came other offspring.  =0AAdvocacy and teachin=
g of forcible overthrow of government as an abstract=0A principle is immune=
 from prosecution.  <em>Yates v. United States,</em> <span class=3D"l-lefto=
ver"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/354/298/case.htm=
l">354 U. S. 298</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D=
"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/354/298/case.html#318">354 U. S=
. 318</a></span>.  But an "active" member, who has a guilty knowledge and i=
ntent of the aim to overthrow the Government </div><div><a href=3D"" class=
=3D"page-number" name=3D"454">Page 395 U. S. 454</a></div><div> by violence=
, <em>Noto v. United States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"htt=
p://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/367/290/case.html">367 U. S. 290</a=
></span>, may be prosecuted.  <em>Scales v. United States,</em> <span class=
=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/367/2=
03/case.html">367 U. S. 203</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"=
><a
 href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/367/203/case.html#228">=
367 U. S. 228</a></span>.=0A  And the power to investigate, backed by the p=
owerful sanction of =0Acontempt, includes the power to determine which of t=
he two categories =0Afits the particular witness.  <em>Barenblatt v. United=
 States,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.c=
om/cases/federal/us/360/109/case.html">360 U. S. 109</a></span>,  <span cla=
ss=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federa=
l/us/360/109/case.html#130">360 U. S. 130</a></span>.=0A  And so the invest=
igator roams at will through all of the beliefs of =0Athe witness, ransacki=
ng his conscience and his innermost thoughts.</div>=0A<div>Judge Learned Ha=
nd, who wrote for the Court of Appeals in affirming the judgment in <em>Den=
nis,</em>=0A coined the "not improbable" test, 183 F.2d 201, 214, which thi=
s Court =0Aadopted and which Judge Hand preferred over the "clear and prese=
nt =0Adanger" test.  Indeed, in his book, The Bill of Rights 59 (1958), in =
=0Areferring to Holmes' creation of the "clear and present danger" test, he=
=0A said, "I cannot help thinking that, for once, Homer nodded."</div>=0A<d=
iv>My own view is quite different.  I see no place in the regime of the =0A=
First Amendment for any "clear and present danger" test, whether strict =0A=
and tight, as some would make it, or free-wheeling, as the Court in <em>Den=
nis</em> rephrased it.</div>=0A<div>When one reads the opinions closely and=
 sees when and how the "clear =0Aand present danger" test has been applied,=
 great misgivings are aroused.=0A  First, the threats were often loud, but =
always puny, and made serious =0Aonly by judges so wedded to the <em>status=
 quo</em> that critical analysis made them nervous.  Second, the test was s=
o twisted and perverted in <em>Dennis</em>=0A as to make the trial of those=
 teachers of Marxism an all-out political =0Atrial which was part and parce=
l of the cold war that has eroded =0Asubstantial parts of the First Amendme=
nt.</div>=0A<div>Action is often a method of expression, and within the pro=
tection of the First Amendment.</div>=0A<div>Suppose one tears up his own c=
opy of the Constitution in eloquent protest to a decision of this Court.  M=
ay he be indicted? </div><div><a href=3D"" class=3D"page-number" name=3D"45=
5">Page 395 U. S. 455</a></div>=0A<div>Suppose one rips his own Bible to sh=
reds to celebrate his departure =0Afrom one "faith" and his embrace of athe=
ism.  May he be indicted?</div>=0A<div>Last Term, the Court held in <em>Uni=
ted States v. O'Brien,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://su=
preme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/391/367/case.html">391 U. S. 367</a></spa=
n>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.co=
m/cases/federal/us/391/367/case.html#382">391 U. S. 382</a></span>,=0A that=
 a registrant under Selective Service who burned his draft card in =0Aprote=
st of the war in Vietnam could be prosecuted.  The First Amendment =0Awas t=
endered as a defense and rejected, the Court saying:</div>=0A<div>"The issu=
ance of certificates indicating the registration and =0Aeligibility classif=
ication of individuals is a legitimate and =0Asubstantial administrative ai=
d in the functioning of this system.  And =0Alegislation to insure the cont=
inuing availability of issued certificates=0A serves a legitimate and subst=
antial purpose in the system's =0Aadministration."</div>=0A<div>391 U.S. at=
  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/c=
ases/federal/us/391/367/case.html#377">391 U. S. 377</a></span>-378.</div>=
=0A<div>But O'Brien was not prosecuted for not having his draft card =0Aava=
ilable when asked for by a federal agent.  He was indicted, tried, =0Aand c=
onvicted for burning the card.  And this Court's affirmance of that=0A conv=
iction was not, with all respect, consistent with the First =0AAmendment.</=
div>=0A<div>The act of praying often involves body posture and movement, as=
 well =0Aas utterances.  It is nonetheless protected by the Free Exercise C=
lause.=0A  Picketing, as we have said on numerous occasions, is "free speec=
h =0Aplus."  <em>See Bakery Drivers Local v. Wohl,</em> <span class=3D"l-le=
ftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/315/769/case.=
html">315 U. S. 769</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=
=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/315/769/case.html#775">315 U=
. S. 775</a></span> (DOUGLAS, J., concurring); <em>Giboney v. Empire Storag=
e Co.,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com=
/cases/federal/us/336/490/case.html">336 U. S. 490</a></span>,  <span class=
=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/=
us/336/490/case.html#501">336 U. S. 501</a></span>; <em>Hughes v. Superior =
Court,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com=
/cases/federal/us/339/460/case.html">339 U. S. 460</a></span>,  <span class=
=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/=
us/339/460/case.html#465">339 U. S. 465</a></span>; <em>Labor Board v. Frui=
t Packers,</em> <span
 class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us=
/377/58/case.html">377 U. S. 58</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitaf=
ter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/377/58/case.html=
#77">377 U. S. 77</a></span> (BLACK, J., concurring), <em>and id.</em> at  =
<span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter">377 U. S. 93</span> (HARLAN, J., dissent=
ing); <em>Cox v. Louisiana,</em> <span class=3D"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http=
://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/379/559/case.html">379 U. S. 559</a>=
</span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a href=3D"http://supreme.just=
ia.com/cases/federal/us/379/559/case.html#578">379 U. S. 578</a></span> (op=
inion of BLACK, J.); <em>Food Employees v. Logan Plaza,</em> <span class=3D=
"l-leftover"><a href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/391/308/=
case.html">391 U. S. 308</a></span>,  <span class=3D"l-normaldigitafter"><a=
 href=3D"http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/391/308/case.html#326">=
391 U. S.
 326</a></span>=0A (DOUGLAS, J., concurring).  That means that it can be re=
gulated when it=0A comes to the "plus" or "action" side of the protest.  It=
 can be =0Aregulated as to </div><div><a href=3D"" class=3D"page-number" na=
me=3D"456">Page 395 U. S. 456</a></div><div> the number of pickets and the =
place and hours (<em>see Cox v. Louisiana, supra</em>), because traffic and=
 other community problems would otherwise suffer.</div>=0A<div>But none of =
these considerations is implicated in the symbolic protest of the Vietnam w=
ar in the burning of a draft card.</div>=0A<div>One's beliefs have long bee=
n thought to be sanctuaries which government could not invade.  <em>Barenbl=
att</em>=0A is one example of the ease with which that sanctuary can be vio=
lated.  =0AThe lines drawn by the Court between the criminal act of being a=
n =0A"active" Communist and the innocent act of being a nominal or inactive=
 =0ACommunist mark the difference only between deep and abiding belief and =
=0Acasual or uncertain belief.  But I think that all matters of belief are =
=0Abeyond the reach of subpoenas or the probings of investigators.  That is=
=0A why the invasions of privacy made by investigating committees were =0An=
otoriously unconstitutional.  That is the deep-seated fault in the =0Ainfam=
ous loyalty security hearings which, since 1947, when President =0ATruman l=
aunched them, have processed 20,000,000 men and women.  Those =0Ahearings w=
ere primarily concerned with one's thoughts, ideas, beliefs, =0Aand convict=
ions.  They were the most blatant violations of the First =0AAmendment we h=
ave ever known.</div>=0A<div>The line between what is permissible and not s=
ubject to control and =0Awhat may be made impermissible and subject to regu=
lation is the line =0Abetween ideas and overt acts.</div>=0A<div>The exampl=
e usually given by those who would punish speech is the case of one who fal=
